  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 9% discount rate for Amphenol?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Amphenol is an established, resilient manufacturer, but still exposed to macroeconomic and hardware cycles. A 9% discount rate gives a balanced premium over the 10-year treasury (4.18%) without being overly punitive.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why did Amphenol's FCF and Debt jump so much in 2025?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Amphenol executed massive acquisitions in 2025, notably completing deals like the acquisition of CommScope's mobile networks business. This structurally increased revenue and cash flows while simultaneously exploding the debt load to finance the purchases.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does this DCF account for future acquisitions?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">It accounts for them implicitly through the 10% sustained FCF growth rate. Organic growth alone might be mid-single-digits, so the 10% rate assumes management continues to successfully deploy capital into smaller bolt-on acquisitions.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

